"content": "1. Clockwise and anticlockwise moment 3. Liquid pressure and atmospheric pressure\n\n**Must know**\n• Some illustrations and applications of moment of forces.\n• According to the sign convention followed, anticlockwise moment is taken to be positive but clockwise moment is taken to be negative.\n• Moment of the force, tau = F × d = 2.5 N × 0.4 m = 1.0 N m.\n• Here, force, F = 12 N and moment of a force, tau = 4.2 N m.\n• Moment~of~a~force=F_1 × d_1=8 N × 0.18 m=1.44 N m.\n• beginarrayl Pressure (P) = displaystyle F/A qquad = frac250 N0.2 m^2 = 1250 N/m^2 or 1250 Pa endarray.\n• Foundations of high-rise buildings are kept wide so as to reduce pressure on the ground.\n• A liquid contained in a vessel exerts thrust at all points below its free surface and thus exerts a liquid pressure.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n• Here, force, F = 12 N and moment of a force, tau = not N m.\n• Foundations of high-rise buildings are kept wide so as to reduce pressure on the ground.\n• Atmospheric pressure decreases with an increase in altitude.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **Atmospheric pressure** — associated with : Pressure exerted by the atmospheric air\n• **Barometer** — associated with : A device used to measure atmospheric pressure\n• **Liquid pressure** — associated with : The pressure exerted by a liquid\n• **Pressure** — associated with : The normal force (thrust) acting per unit surface area\n• **Thrust** — associated with : The total normal force exerted by an object on a given surface\n• **Column A** — associated with Column B\n\nAlso revise:\n• Liquid pressure depends upon the density of a liquid.\n• Liquid pressure remains the same in all directions at a given depth.\n• H = Height of the liquid column above that point.\n• So, the air from outside exerts pressure on the walls of the can and crushes it.",
