"subtopic": "9. G. Differentiate between the following",
"content": "5. Energy possessed by an object due to its configuration or change in configuration 1. Kinetic energy and gravitational potential energy\n\n**Must know**\n• Solve simple problems based on kinetic energy.\n• Solve simple problems based on gravitational potential energy.\n• Interconversion of potential energy and kinetic energy.\n• Although we are familiar with the term 'energy', we shall read in detail about two common forms of energy, namely, kinetic energy and gravitational potential energy and their measurement.\n• A strong wind can uproot big trees due to its kinetic energy.\n• Kinetic energy of wind can be used to run windmills.\n• Conclusion: The kinetic energy of moving heavier hammer is more than that of the lighter hammer, i.e., the amount of kinetic energy depends on the mass of the moving object.\n• Conclusion is defined as The kinetic energy of moving heavier hammer is more than that of the lighter hammer, i.e., the amount of kinetic energy depends on the mass of the moving object.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Potential energy may be converted into kinetic energy and vice versa.\n• 1 megawatt=1 MW=10^6 W=10^3 kW.\n• Potential energy of a suitcase of mass 24 kg when taken to the roof of a multistorey building is 7200 J.\n• Energy possessed by an object in motion.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **Kinetic energy** — associated with Gravitational potential energy\n• **Elastic potential energy** — associated with : Energy possessed by an object at rest due to its characteristic configuration (shape and size)\n• **Energy** — associated with : Capability of doing work\n• **Gravitational potential energy** — associated with : Energy possessed by an object at rest due to its position above the ground\n• **Potential energy** — associated with : Energy possessed by an object at rest due to its specific position or configuration\n• **Although we** — familiar with the term 'energy', we shall read in detail about two common forms of energy, namely, kinetic energy and gravitational potential energy and their measurement\n\nAlso revise:\n• From this, it is concluded that kinetic energy depends on the speed of an object.\n• 》Speed of the object: Greater the speed of the object, greater the kinetic energy possessed by it.\n• Kinetic energy of the bullet, KE = 1/2mv^2 = 1/2 × 0.01 × 200 × 200 = 200 J.\n• Kinetics energy of the ball, KE = 1/2mv^2 = 1/2 × 0.15 × 40 × 40 = 120 J.",
