"type": "note",
"subtopic": "8. Real Images Formed by a Concave Mirror",
"content": "The nature, position and size of the image formed by a concave mirror depends on the position of the object placed in front of it. Here, we are discussing following five cases in which the image formed is a real image Do you know that a concave mirror can form either a real or a virtual image of an object placed in front of it depending upon the distance between the object and the concave mirror? Yes, I know. I also know that a convex mirror always forms a virtual image of an\n\n**Must know**\n• Spherical mirrors can create various forms of images based on the nature of spherical mirrors and the position of the object placed in front of them, making them useful for various purposes.\n• Concave mirrors are used as make-up and shaving mirrors because they form erect and enlarged image of face of a person situated just near the mirror.\n• Moreover, the path of the light ray behind the mirror should also be shown by a dotted line.\n• Concave mirrors are used in solar cookers and solar furnaces to focus the sun radiation at a place.\n• Convex mirrors are used as rear-view mirrors in vehicles because they create erect and smaller images of vehicles coming from behind.\n• Concave mirrors are used as make-up (shaving) mirrors and as reflectors in torches, headlights of automobiles and in solar cookers and solar furnaces.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Case 4 is defined as When the object is placed between the focus and the centre of curvature.\n• Dispersion of light happens because sunlight is made up of seven different colours.\n• State one use of a concave mirror.\n• Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n• Concave mirrors not used as make-up and shaving mirrors because they form erect and enlarged image of face of a person situated just near th\n• Moreover, the path of the light ray behind the mirror not also be shown by a dotted line.",
