"subtopic": "5. Different liquids expand differently",
"content": "For equal rise in temperature, different liquids expand differently. For example, ether on heating expands more than alcohol and alcohol expands more than water. This can be shown by the following activity: Water shows an anomalous expansion. When water is heated from 0°C to 4°C, its volume contracts. However, on heating beyond 4°C its volume expands. Thus, for a given mass of water, the volume is minimum at 4°C\n\n**Must know**\n• Whenever an object is heated, it expands.\n• Using a water tub and a burner, start heating the flask.\n• Later on, water is heated up and expands.\n• Turpentine oil 9.6 Alcohol (ethyl) 11.9 Alcohol (methyl).\n• Cases too expand on heating and their expansion is even greater than that of liquids.\n• Different gases expand differently when heated to a given rise in temperature.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Fill: Alcohol — Turpentine oil 9.6 Alcohol (ethyl) 11.9 Alcohol (methyl).",
