"content": "as also expand when heated and they expand much more than liquids or solids. This is because molecules are very loosely packed as compared to molecules in a solid or a liquid. Moreover, volumes of all the gases have equal expansion for a given rise in temperature\n\n**Must know**\n• Compare expansivity in solids, liquids and gases.\n• Boiling: When a liquid is heated at a particular temperature, liquid molecules gain sufficient energy so as to overcome the intermolecular forces present between liquid molecules and become independent and free.\n• Evaporation: It is the process where a liquid changes into its vapour form at any temperature, but it only happens at the surface of the liquid.\n• Most substances, whether solid or liquid or gas, expand when heated and contract when cooled.\n• Generally, gases expand much more than liquids and liquids expand much more than solids for the same rise (increase) in temperature.\n• Before fitting, the rims are heated so that they expand and fly over the wheels.\n• Moreover, volume expansion of liquids is generally much than expansion of solids for a given rise in temperature.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Later on, water is heated up and expands.\n• Steel girders supporting a bridge are mounted on the rollers rather than being fixed in the walls of the pillars.\n• Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n• Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n• Boiling: When a liquid is not at a particular temperature, liquid molecules gain sufficient energy so as to overcome the intermolecular forc\n• Compare expansivity in solids, liquids and gases.",
