"subtopic": "1. Introduction",
"content": "☐ describe safety components (fuses, circuit breakers) conduct scientific experiments keeping in mind all the parameters In this chapter, you will explore the fundamental concepts that how electrical circuits work. As you all are familiar with the flow of electricity through an electric circuit, you will begin by revising key terms like potential difference (voltage), electric current and electric resistance. The chapter will introduce new concepts such as electric power and\n\n**Must know**\n• So far, you know electricity due to flow of electric charges.\n• A schematic diagram of a household electric circuit.\n• Simple rules for the safe use of electricity at home.\n• Voltmeter is used to measure voltage/potential difference.\n• 1k ilowatt=1k W=1000W=10^3W.\n• 1 megawatt=1 m W=10^6 W=1000 kW.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n• Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n• Fill: Attraction — Attraction is a sure test for electrification.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **Voltmeter** — used to measure voltage/potential difference\n• **Electricity** — supplied to our houses via overhead wires (or cables) on poles or underground cables made of copper or aluminium\n\nAlso revise:\n• Here, potential difference, V = 220 V and current, I = 0.1 A.\n• 1 W h=1 W × 1 h=1 W × (60 × 60) s=3600 W s=3600 J.\n• 1 kW h=1000 W h=3.6 × 10^6J.\n• = 1200 W h = 1200/1000 kW h = 1.2 kW h.",
