"type": "note",
"subtopic": "2. Mmonly Used Electrical Terms",
"content": "Electric current: Electric current is defined as the rate of flow of electric charge in an electric Electric~current,I=Charge~flown,Q/Time,t The SI unit of electric current is ampere (A), which was named after the name of scientist Andre-Marie Ampère\n\n**Must know**\n• Cell (or a battery composed of multiple cells).\n• André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836) was a French physicist who founded and named the science of electrodynamics, now known as electromagnetism.\n• Ammeter is used to measure current flowing through a circuit directly in ampere.\n• Electric potential difference: Electric potential difference between two given points in an electric circuit is defined as the amount of work done for moving a unit positive charge between these two points.\n• Positive charge flows from higher potential (+ve terminal) to lower potential (re terminal).\n• Voltmeter is used to measure voltage/potential difference.\n• Resistance and resistor: Any element present in an electric circuit which causes restriction of the flow of electric current is called resistor.\n• Electric bulb, fluorescent tube, CFL, electric fan, electric heater, geyser, electric mixer grinder, etc., are some common examples of resistors.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• After the electric meter, live and neutral wires are connected to a distribution box.\n• Finally, the electric charge could pass to the earth through his body.\n• Resistance and resistor: Any element present in an electric circuit which causes restriction of the flow of electric current is called resistor.\n• Electric resistance is said to be one ohm if a potential difference of 1 volt is required to maintain a flow of 1 ampere current.\n• Electrical energy consumed in an electric circuit when a current l flows for time t on applying a potential difference not is given by.\n• André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836) was a French physicist who founded and named the science of electrodynamics, now known as electromagnetism.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **Electric current** — defined as Electric current is defined as the rate of flow of electric charge in an electric\n• **Ammeter** — used to measure current flowing through a circuit directly in ampere\n• **Voltmeter** — used to measure voltage/potential difference\n• **Electric resistance** — usually denoted by the symbol R\n\nAlso revise:\n• Electric resistance is usually denoted by the symbol R.\n• Electric resistance is said to be one ohm if a potential difference of 1 volt is required to maintain a flow of 1 ampere current.\n• Let, on applying a potential difference V, a current I flow through a resistor R.\n• Then, as per relation, I = Q/t, the total amount of charge flown,.",
"source": "icse",
"examTip": "Read in order, then tap Practice linked questions — notes cover what exam questions ask.",
