"topicId": "ch8-electricity",
"type": "note",
"subtopic": "3. Rating of Electrical Appliances",
"content": "might have seen words like 100 W, 220 V marked on an incandescent electric bulb or 40 W, V marked on a fluorescent tube, etc. When we say that an electric bulb is rated as 100 W, V, it means that the power consumed by the electric bulb is 100 W when operated on 220 V. Again, rating of 40 W, 220 V on a fluorescent tube means that the tube will be supply. Again, rating of 40 W when operated on 220 V electric supply s power rating of an electric appliance/device/gadget indicates\n\n**Must know**\n• Appliance/device relates to Power (W), Voltage (V), and Appliance/device.\n• CFL relates to 5 – 18, 220, and 10. Desert cooler.\n• Electrical energy, E = Voltage, V × current, I × time, t.\n• Maximum safe current,I=fracPower rating of appliance,POperating voltage,V.\n• Here, rated power, P = 11 W and operating voltage, V = 220 V.\n• Maximum value of safe current, I = P/V = 11/220 = 1/20 A = 0.05 A.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Here, rated power, P = 11 W and operating voltage, V = 220 V.\n• An electric heater draws more current than a LED bulb.\n• Again, rating of 40 W, 220 V on a fluorescent tube means that the tube will be supply.\n• Now, touch the glass rod with the insulator A.\n• Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n• Calculate the maximum safe current not through the bulb and the resistance of the bulb filament in the working condition.\n• Ectrical energy consumed per day, E = P × t.\n• Fill: Voltage — Appliance/device relates to Power (W), Voltage (V), and Appliance/device.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **Estimate the average time for which each appliance** — used per day\n\nAlso revise:\n• Calculate the maximum safe current flowing through the bulb and the resistance of the bulb filament in the working condition.\n• Here, power of the bulb, P = 100 W and operating voltage, V = 220 V.\n• Maximum safe current flowing through the bulb, I = P/V = 100/200 A = 5/11 A.\n• Electrical energy in kW h (or commercial units)=fracV(in volts) × I(in amperes) × t(in hours)1000.",
