"id": "phy-s8-sec_04",
"topicId": "ch8-electricity",
"type": "note",
"subtopic": "4. Activity 1 SEL Self-Awareness",
"content": "Compare your estimated value of electricity consumed in units with the bill received from the electricity supply company To reduce our electricity bill, we should switch off an electrical appliance immediately after its use In our homes, electricity is supplied at 220 V. However, electricity is transmitted from one station to another at very high voltages ranging from 11 kV to 400 kV or even more. This is done so as to minimise loss of electrical energy during transmission. T\n\n**Must know**\n• Electrical energy, E = Voltage, V × current, I × time, t.\n• Here, rated power, P = 11 W and operating voltage, V = 220 V.\n• Here, power of the bulb, P = 100 W and operating voltage, V = 220 V.\n• A person uses a fluorescent tube of 40 W rating for 10 hours a day.\n• Here, power of fluorescent tube, P = 40 W and time of use per day, t = 10 h.\n• Ectrical energy consumed per day, E = P × t.\n• A colour TV, rated 150 W, is being operated 8 hours per day.\n• Here, power rating of TV, P = 150 W; time for which used daily, t = 8 h; number of days, 30 and cost of electricity = ₹6 per unit.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• Describe the construction of a gold leaf electroscope.\n• Ectrical energy consumed per day, E = P × t.\n• Fill: W × 10 — beginalignedE&=P × t&=40 W × 10 h=400 W h=400/1000kW h=0.4 kW hendaligned.\n• 1 megawatt=1 m W=10^6 W=1000 kW.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **A colour TV, rated 150 W,** — being operated 8 hours per day\n• **Estimate the average time for which each appliance** — used per day\n• **Electricity** — supplied to our houses via overhead wires (or cables) on poles or underground cables made of copper or aluminium\n\nAlso revise:\n• Electrical energy consumed per day, E = 150 × 8 Wh.\n• Total electrical energy consumed in 1 month of 30 days = nE = 30 × 1.2 kW h = 1000 kW h = 1.2 kW h.\n• Estimate the average time for which each appliance is used per day.\n• Calculate the electricity consumed per day in your home in kW h.",
"source": "icse",
