"type": "note",
"subtopic": "6. A Schematic Diagram of a Household Electric Circuit",
"content": "A schematic diagram of a household electric circuit has been shown in the following Fig. 8.2 As shown in the figure, a main switch of high current rating (about 50 A or even more) is connected to the live wire just before the electric meter. This fuse is called the electricity board's (or electric company) fuse and only board (or company) persons are authorised to handle it. The rating of the device depends on the load sanctioned for a house After the electricity board's fuse\n\n**Must know**\n• After the electricity board's fuse, the live and neutral wires are connected to an electric meter usually mounted on outer wall of the house.\n• All electrical appliances are connected in parallel so that each appliance works independently and separate on/off switch may be provided with each appliance.\n• A kilowatt-hour (kW h) is the standard unit of electrical energy.\n• An electric meter has a dial or screen in which numbers keep on changing as the electricity is consumed by various appliances in our homes.\n• A switch is always connected along with live wire.\n• A Miniature Circuit Breaker (MCB) is an alternative arrangement for fuse.\n• Earthing (grounding) of an electric circuit is particularly useful for those appliances which have a metallic body, e.g., electric iron, toaster, table fan, refrigerator, etc.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• A lightning conductor consists of a thick copper strip fitted on the outside of a building.\n• Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n• Direct contact of a not with a live wire leads to a severe shock to him and it may even prove fatal.\n• Earthing (grounding) of an electric circuit is particularly useful for those appliances which have a metallic body, e.g., electric iron, toa\n• A switch is always connected along with live wire.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **Electricity** — supplied to our houses via overhead wires (or cables) on poles or underground cables made of copper or aluminium\n\nAlso revise:\n• Direct contact of a person with a live wire leads to a severe shock to him and it may even prove fatal.\n• Defects in electric circuits like loose joints, improper insulation of wires and defective switches, sockets, plugs, etc., may cause sparkling.\n• Switches, sockets, plugs, etc., may cause sparking and may lead to fire.\n• A person gets a severe electric shock on touching a.",
