"subtopic": "23. K. Numerical Problems",
"content": "1. An electric current of 0.3 A flows through the filament of an electric bulb when connected to a 200 V mains supply. What is the electric power? 2. A fluorescent tube is marked 40 W, 220 V. What current is flowing through it when being operated? 3. A washerman uses an electric iron for 6 hours. If the power rating of iron be 450 W, how much energy in kW h has been consumed by him?\n\n**Must know**\n• Fluorescent tube (4 feet) relates to 36 – 40, 220, and 9. Refrigerator (165 L).\n• Commonly, it is known as current electricity.\n• Again, rating of 40 W, 220 V on a fluorescent tube means that the tube will be supply.\n• Again, rating of 40 W when operated on 220 V electric supply.\n• An electric bulb is marked 100 W, 220 V.\n• Maximum safe current flowing through the bulb, I = P/V = 100/200 A = 5/11 A.\n• Calculate the electricity consumed per day in your home in kW h.\n• = nE = 30 × 1.2 kW h = 36 kW h = 36 units.\n\n**Answers for linked questions**\n• A person uses a fluorescent tube of 40 W rating for 10 hours a day.\n• Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n• An electric current of 0.3 A flows through the filament of an electric bulb when connected to a 200 V mains supply.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• **Commonly, it** — known as current electricity\n• **Electric current** — defined as Electric current is defined as the rate of flow of electric charge in an electric\n• **Again, rating of 40 W, 220 V on a fluorescent tube** — that the tube will be supply\n• **An electric bulb** — marked 100 W, 220 V\n• **Electricity** — supplied to our houses via overhead wires (or cables) on poles or underground cables made of copper or aluminium\n\nAlso revise:\n• An electric current of 0.3 A flows through the filament of an electric bulb when connected to a 200 V mains supply.\n• A fluorescent tube is marked 40 W, 220 V.\n• A washerman uses an electric iron for 6 hours.\n• Calculate the cost of running a geyser of 2 kW power rating for 2 hours.",
"source": "icse",
"examTip": "Read in order, then tap Practice linked questions — notes cover what exam questions ask.",
